04381nam a22007575i 9780823282364DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232823647 a10.1515/97808232823642doi  a(DE-B1597)554932  a(OCoLC)1062418750  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB2137 7aLIT0041502bisacsh04a1942231 aLacoue-Labarthe, Philippe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPoetics of History :bRousseau and the Theater of Originary Mimesis /cPhilippe Lacoue-Labarthe. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- t1 -- t2 -- t3 -- t1 -- t2 -- t3 -- tNotes 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRousseau's opposition to the theater is well known: Far from purging the passions, it serves only to exacerbate them, and to render them hypocritical. But is it possible that Rousseau's texts reveal a different conception of theatrical imitation, a more originary form of mimesis? Over and against Heidegger's dismissal of Rousseau in the 1930s, and in the wake of classic readings by Jacques Derrida and Jean Starobinski, Lacoue-Labarthe asserts the deeply philosophical importance of Rousseau as a thinker who, without formalizing it as such, established a dialectical logic that would determine the future of philosophy: an originary theatricality arising from a dialectic between "nature" and its supplements.Beginning with a reading of Rousseau's Discourse on Inequality, Lacoue-Labarthe brings out this dialectic in properly philosophical terms, revealing nothing less than a transcendental thinking of origins. For Rousseau, the origin has the form of a "scene"-that is, of theater. On this basis, Rousseau's texts on the theater, especially the Letter to d'Alembert, emerge as an incisive interrogation of Aristotle's Poetics. This can be read not in the false and conventional interpretation of this text that Rousseau had inherited, but rather in relation to its fundamental concepts, mimesis and katharsis, and in Rousseau's interpretation of Greek theater itself. If for Rousseau mimesis is originary, a transcendental structure, katharsis is in turn the basis of a dialectical movement, an Aufhebung that will translate the word itself (for, as Lacoue-Labarthe reminds us, Aufheben translates katharein). By reversing the facilities of the Platonic critique, Rousseau inaugurates what we could call the philosophical theater of the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aHistory. 0aImitation. 0aPhilosophy. 4aAristotle, Poetics. 4aAufhebung. 4aRousseau. 4acatharsis. 4adialectics. 4amimesis. 4apurgation. 4atheater. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh1 aFort, Jeff08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071028140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823282364zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823282364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823282364.jpg  a978-3-11-071028-1  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK